No player scored more goals in the history of TotalEnergies Africa Cup of Nations (AFCON) than Samuel Eto’o. The Cameroonian legend netted a record of 18 goals in six editions he played for The Indomitable Lions of Cameroon. Eto’o who played for the likes of giants Real Madrid and Barcelona (Spain), Inter Milan (Italy) and Chelsea (England) among others, donned Cameroon short in 118 caps, scoring 56 goals in the process; a national record. 18 of these goals came in the African flagship competition as Eto’o set himself as the all-time record goal scorer, overtaking Cote d’Ivoire’s Laurent Pokou (14 goals). Eto’o was among the Cameroon team that won back to back AFCON titles in 2000 and 2002. He also took part in four more editions (2004, 2006, 2008 and 2010), scoring at least a goal in each of them, which is also a record (scoring in six different AFCON editions) that he shares with Zambia’s Kalusha Bwalya and Ghana’s Asamoah Gyan. Lukaku Apologises, Returns To Chelsea Squad Morocco Join Early Birds In Cameroon At the Ghana/Nigeria 2000 edition, Eto’o scored four goals (4 goals); at Mali 2022, he scored a goal as well as at Tunisia 2004 where he also scored a goal. At Egypt 2006, he emerged as the tournament’s top scorer with five goals and repeated same feat at Ghana 2008 where he also scored five goals and emerged as the tournament’s top scorer. At Angola 2010, he however scored two goals to bring his total goals to 18.